<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>
<!-- Widgets increment (Runway 0.10.0); progress bar polish (0.40.0). The
     Prüfung home-screen widget's layout: the ready-by line, then a thin
     weekly progress bar (below), then the "This week ..." line, then the
     exam anchor line, smallest and dimmest, last. Rendered by
     PruefungWidgetProvider.java; colours for widget_line1 and which of the
     two progress-bar views is shown are set programmatically there
     (calm/tight/late for the text, sky-vs-emerald for the bar), everything
     else here is static.

     0.40.0: this used to be "three plain TextViews, no progress bars or
     icons" (RUNWAY_PRUFUNG_PLAN.md §4.1's "a bar at 8% is demoralising"
     rule) — but that rule is about the PER-TOPIC coverage bars the app
     deliberately never draws, not about the app's ONE sanctioned exception:
     ExamOverview.tsx's weekly bar, which fills across days and resets every
     Monday rather than accumulating into a months-long low-percentage
     indictment (see that screen's own comment). This widget mirrors that
     one bar, and only that one — the topic list still stays plain numbers
     on the live screen, unchanged.

     Two ProgressBar views (widget_progress_sky / widget_progress_emerald),
     layered in a FrameLayout at the same position rather than one bar whose
     colour is changed at runtime — RemoteViews cannot reliably retint a
     drawable's tint across every API level this app's minSdk spans, so
     "two pre-coloured variants, toggle which one is visible" is the robust
     RemoteViews idiom here (see PruefungWidgetProvider.java's own comment
     on this same point). Both are given android:progress="0" here so the
     widget-picker preview (m1 below) shows an honest EMPTY bar, matching
     this increment's "render honestly at zero" rule rather than looking
     falsely progressed in the picker.

     m1: the android:text values below are visible ONLY in the widget
     picker's preview (no previewImage is set — see widget_pruefung_info.xml
     — so the picker falls back to rendering this initialLayout as-is).
     PruefungWidgetProvider.onUpdate ALWAYS overwrites every one of these
     views the moment the widget is actually placed on a home screen;
     nothing below is ever shown to Deepak on a real, placed widget.

     0.41.0 (daily shape): widget_line_today sits between the progress row
     and widget_line3 — "Today: 1 of 3 sprints." / "Rest day.", hidden
     (GONE) entirely when no dailyTarget is set. Coloured via a direct
     setTextColor(int) call, NOT the two-pre-coloured-view toggle the
     progress bar above uses — a plain TextView's text colour is a
     @RemotableViewMethod RemoteViews can set reliably on any API level this
     app's minSdk spans, unlike retinting a ProgressDrawable, which is what
     forced the bar's two-view workaround in the first place (see
     PruefungWidgetProvider's own comment on that).

     Headline swap (0.41.1): widget_line_today is now DUAL-PURPOSE, not
     single-purpose the way it was at 0.41.0 — RemoteViews has no
     view-reordering primitive, so "the day-sized number becomes the
     headline when a daily target is set" (ExamOverview.tsx's same swap,
     mirrored here) can't be done by moving a view up the layout; it's done
     by moving CONTENT between two already-existing, fixed-position slots
     instead. With a live daily target: widget_line1 above goes bold with
     the Today count (and picks up its own colour, set programmatically —
     see PruefungWidgetProvider.applyHeadline), and THIS view is repurposed
     to hold whatever text widget_line1 would otherwise have shown (the
     ready-by projection), at this view's own existing 12sp size, state-
     coloured the same way widget_line1's ready-by text always was. With no
     daily target (or a stale snapshot — see applyHeadline's own staleness-
     guard comment), this view goes back to being exactly what 0.41.0 built:
     hidden, and widget_line1 shows the ready-by text as it always did. The
     id keeps its 0.41.0 name (widget_line_today) rather than being renamed
     to something mode-neutral — renaming here would touch this file and
     PruefungWidgetProvider.java for a cosmetic gain only; this comment is
     the source of truth for what the view actually does now. -->
<LinearLayout xmlns:android="http://schemas.android.com/apk/res/android"
    android:id="@+id/widget_root"
    android:layout_width="match_parent"
    android:layout_height="match_parent"
    android:orientation="vertical"
    android:gravity="start|center_vertical"
    android:background="@drawable/widget_bg"
    android:padding="14dp">

    <TextView
        android:id="@+id/widget_line1"
        android:layout_width="wrap_content"
        android:layout_height="wrap_content"
        android:textSize="18sp"
        android:textStyle="bold"
        android:textColor="#F1F5F9"
        android:maxLines="1"
        android:text="Ready by 14 Dec" />

    <!-- Weekly progress bar row (0.40.0) — see this file's own header
         comment. match_parent width so it reads as a full-width tactical
         surface, not a token sliver; 6dp height per the increment spec,
         comfortably tappable-looking without dominating a 64dp-tall
         widget. -->
    <FrameLayout
        android:id="@+id/widget_progress_row"
        android:layout_width="match_parent"
        android:layout_height="6dp"
        android:layout_marginTop="6dp">

        <ProgressBar
            android:id="@+id/widget_progress_sky"
            style="@android:style/Widget.ProgressBar.Horizontal"
            android:layout_width="match_parent"
            android:layout_height="match_parent"
            android:max="100"
            android:progress="0"
            android:progressDrawable="@drawable/progress_sky" />

        <ProgressBar
            android:id="@+id/widget_progress_emerald"
            style="@android:style/Widget.ProgressBar.Horizontal"
            android:layout_width="match_parent"
            android:layout_height="match_parent"
            android:max="100"
            android:progress="0"
            android:visibility="gone"
            android:progressDrawable="@drawable/progress_emerald" />

    </FrameLayout>

    <!-- Daily shape (0.41.0) — see this file's own header comment above.
         Same 12sp/slate-400 starting look as widget_line3 below (its
         "not met" state IS this default XML colour; "met" overrides it to
         emerald #6EE7B7 at render time), 6dp below the bar the same way
         widget_line3 used to sit before this line was inserted between
         them. -->
    <TextView
        android:id="@+id/widget_line_today"
        android:layout_width="wrap_content"
        android:layout_height="wrap_content"
        android:layout_marginTop="6dp"
        android:textSize="12sp"
        android:textColor="#94A3B8"
        android:maxLines="1"
        android:text="Today: 1 of 3 sprints." />

    <TextView
        android:id="@+id/widget_line3"
        android:layout_width="wrap_content"
        android:layout_height="wrap_content"
        android:layout_marginTop="2dp"
        android:textSize="12sp"
        android:textColor="#94A3B8"
        android:maxLines="1"
        android:text="This week: 0.0 of 18.4 h" />

    <TextView
        android:id="@+id/widget_line2"
        android:layout_width="wrap_content"
        android:layout_height="wrap_content"
        android:layout_marginTop="2dp"
        android:textSize="11sp"
        android:textColor="#64748B"
        android:maxLines="1"
        android:text="Exam Nov 2026" />

</LinearLayout>
